          </row>
        </table>
        <p rendition="simple:Bodysimple:text|1" style="text-align: right;">Chinese Subjects. Western Subjects (not including drill).</p>
        <p rendition="simple:Bodysimple:text|1" style="text-align: justify;">(The writer cannot give figures for middle school work in the Educational Union, in which he has had no experience.)</p>
        <p rendition="simple:Bodysimple:text|1" style="text-align: justify;">These figures show that while the proportion of hours that we give to each class of subjects is slightly different, the actual number of hours given to Chinese subject, is very little less than it is in the Government schools. The greatest difference of course lies in our substitution of Scripture for Ethics, which in the Government course is taken to include the lives of illustrious patriots. But the fact that last year the Bible was introduced into some of the Government schools in two of the provinces of China indicates that the purpose and value of “The Book” are becoming known.</p>
        <p rendition="simple:Bodysimple:text|1" style="text-align: justify;">In conclusion may the writer make a few suggestions that have come from his reading of the Educational Regulations.</p>
        <list type="ordered">
          <item><anchor xml:id="bookmark6"/>Might we not wisely copy the Chinese in their slowness to change the course of study? The first course was issued in 1904 and the changes not until 1909. We should certainly be “going on to perfection”, but it is a questionable proceeding to be constantly pulling a thing up to make it grow faster.</item>
          <item><anchor xml:id="bookmark7"/>When the belated new regulations for the Senior Primary appear it might be well to bring our course into line by rearranging the order of studying the classics in the various grades.</item>
          <item><anchor xml:id="bookmark8"/>Might we not profitably incorporate in our chang ch’einn a statement of the fact that our course follows in the main that laid down by the Board of Education, and also quote some of the general regulations regarding the aim and general conduct of schools, and the methods of teaching the various-subjects.</item>
          <item><anchor xml:id="bookmark9"/>Could we not give our Chinese fellow teachers some share of the work of the Union? If we cannot have them as delegates at our annual meeting (though, why not?), we can at [line missing in image]<pb cert="high" facs="https://leaf.lincsproject.ca/sites/default/files/2023-05/Educational%20by%20Wallace%20-%206.jpg" xml:space="default"/></item>
        </list>
        <p rendition="simple:Bodysimple:text|1" style="text-align: justify;">every way to arouse on their part as great an interest in the schools of the Educational Union as is aroused in Government school circles by Teachers’ Associations, athletic meets, and visits of inspectors? It might be possible to arrange for prefectural teachers' conventions, where live school questions could be discussed and recommendations be sent to this Annual Meeting. In this way the teachers would feel something of the bigness of the system with which they are concerned. It is undoubtedly a factor in the continued, success of the modern Chinese school system that it is common to the Empire, and is one national movement in which all teachers may have a part. </p>
        <p rendition="simple:Bodysimple:text|1" style="text-align: justify;">(5) It is to be hoped that in the future we may have increasing intercourse with teachers in Government schools, and let them understand that our aims, course of study, and methods are similar to theirs. Probably we can best break down the prejudice at present existing against our schools by such intercourse, showing that we are not trying to make our scholars disloyal to their country, but that we aim to make them good, moral, law-abiding citizens of the Empire. We may thus pave the way for the recognition by the Government school authorities of schools under mission control, and help to bring about complete religious toleration in China. </p>
        <p rendition="simple:Bodysimple:text|1" style="text-align: right;"><persName key="Edward Wilson Wallace" ref="http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q105938574" cert="high" role="aut" type="real">Edward Wilson Wallace</persName>.</p>
